The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, April 16, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, April 15: The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has granted freedom to banks to decide on all aspects, including interest rates and renewal of overdue domestic term deposits, subject to the bank boards laying down a transparent policy. The RBI, in a notification issued here today, said the policy should be non-discretionary and non-discriminatory and the customers should be notified of the terms and conditions at the acceptance of deposit. As per the existing norms, banks are free to renew overdue domestic term deposits at an interest rate prevailing on the date of maturity provided the depositor approaches the bank within 14 days from the date of maturity.																								 Mumbai, April 15: Zee Telefilms Limited has posted a 38.19 per cent rise in its consolidated net profit at Rs 310.17 crore for the financial year ended March 31, 2004 as against Rs 224.45 crore in 2002-03.																								 New Delhi, April 15: Tata Motors has hired Citigroup Inc, J P Morgan Chase and Co, Merrill Lynch amp; Co, and Morgan Stanley to sell foreign currency convertible bonds worth $500 million.																								 Mumbai, April 15: The rupee lost 21 paise from Tuesdays close of 43.77/79 and settled at an 18-day closing low of 43.98/99 per dollar at the forex market today.																								 New Delhi, April 15: Agilent Technologies, a global player in communications, electronics and chemical analysis, said today it would increase its workforce in India to 2,500 from 900 by 2006.
